  <h2 class="section-heading" id="whats-inside" data-jump-label="What's Inside a Skill">What's Inside a Skill</h2>
  <p class="section-description">Your daily briefing skill has exactly two files:</p>

  <table class="compare-table">
    <tr>
      <th>Component</th>
      <th>What It Does</th>
      <th>You Provide</th>
      <th>Claude Handles</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>SKILL.md</strong></td>
      <td>Instructions Claude follows when triggered</td>
      <td>Your data sources, briefing sections, alert logic</td>
      <td>Format, error handling, trigger phrases</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>references/context.md</strong></td>
      <td>Your consolidated knowledge base</td>
      <td>Your role, team, OKRs, Slack channels, key docs</td>
      <td>Structure, organization, fallback data</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <div class="diagram-box">daily-briefing/
├── SKILL.md                    ← Instructions (what Claude does)
└── references/
    └── context.md              ← Your knowledge base (who you are)</div>

  <div class="key-difference">
    <p><strong>Why Skills, Not Folders</strong><br>An earlier version of this training recommended building a folder structure in Cowork with a CLAUDE.md and multiple context files. The Skills approach is better:</p>
  </div>

  <table class="compare-table">
    <tr>
      <th>Cowork Folder Approach</th>
      <th>Claude Skill Approach</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>File system resets between sessions</td>
      <td>Skill persists in your Claude account</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Multiple files to maintain (profile.md, team.md, projects.md, etc.)</td>
      <td>Single consolidated context.md</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Only works in Cowork desktop app</td>
      <td>Works in any Claude interface — web, mobile, desktop</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Can't easily share or move your setup</td>
      <td>Portable .skill file</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>No built-in error handling</td>
      <td>Error handling in the skill instructions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
